yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way investment banking works is that you do a l=
ot of free work for companies, meeting with them frequently to pitch ideas =
and give them advice and listen to their troubles and analyze their finance=
s, in the hope that one day they will hire you to advise them on a merger o=
r a bond deal and pay you a lot of money. Your fee for doing the merger is,=
 generally, very generous, measured against the number of hours that you sp=
end working on the merger. Measured against the number of hours that you sp=
ent=C2=A0<em>pitching=C2=A0</em>that company, and the 20 other companies th=
at=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>mandate you on mergers, it looks more =
reasonable.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Occasionally this process lead=
s to disappointment. There are two slightly different forms of disappointme=
nt:</p> <ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: =
16px 0;"> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You cover Company X intensively=
 for years. You give its chief executive officer a lot of creative ideas, y=
ou do a lot of=C2=A0financial analysis for her, you are always ready with h=
elpful advice. You come to view her as a friend, and you believe that she v=
iews you as a trusted adviser. Then one day you read Company X=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0press release=C2=A0saying that it=C2=A0did a big acquisition with the he=
lp of three banks, none of which are yours. You feel hurt and betrayed. All=
 that work got you nowhere. You resolve (1) never to call her again or (2) =
more realistically, to redouble your efforts and call her even more often s=
o you get in on the next deal.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You c=
over Company X extensively for years, or not, but in any case you come in o=
ne day and say to the CEO =E2=80=9Cyou should buy Company Y, here=E2=80=99s=
 an analysis of why it makes sense, let me introduce you to Company Y=E2=80=
=99s CEO.=E2=80=9D The CEO is intrigued; she reads your analysis and finds =
it compelling. =E2=80=9CSure, introduce us,=E2=80=9D she says. You take her=
 to dinner with Company Y=E2=80=99s CEO. They hit it off. They discuss the =
contours of a deal, but they hit a structural snag. As a creative mergers-a=
nd-acquisitions banker with long experience, you suavely suggest a solution=
 to the snag. =E2=80=9CAh terrific,=E2=80=9D they say, and carry on. It loo=
ks like a deal could work. Everyone leaves the dinner in good spirits. You =
have a nice weekend in the country. On Monday, you read a joint Company X a=
nd Company Y press release announcing that they are doing a merger with the=
 help of three banks, none of which are yours.</li> </ol> <p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">In the first scenario, you are hurt because Company X violated =
the unspoken expectation that you would be rewarded for your work and advic=
e and good coverage. In the second scenario, you are furious because Compan=
y X=C2=A0<em>stole your intellectual property</em>. I mean, not literally, =
not quite. But you went and did the deal for them =E2=80=94=C2=A0or at leas=
t got things started =E2=80=94=C2=A0and they didn=E2=80=99t pay you for tha=
t. In Scenario 1, you didn=E2=80=99t get rewarded with=C2=A0a deal fee for =
your=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>work. In Scenario 2, you didn=E2=80=99t get r=
ewarded with a deal fee for=C2=A0<em>doing some of the deal</em>.</p> <p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here I am being generous to you, the banker. From t=
he client=E2=80=99s perspective, Scenario 2 might look like this:</p> <ul s=
tyle=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Every day, Company X=E2=80=99s CEO comes into t=
he office and gets a dozen calls from investment bankers who want meetings.=
 She has work to do, and can=E2=80=99t say yes to them all, but out of poli=
teness she tries to meet with bankers from time to time. Every one of them =
waltzes in with a pitchbook, all of which say exactly the same thing: =E2=
=80=9CYou should buy Company Y.=E2=80=9D This is obvious! Company Y is Comp=
any X=E2=80=99s big rival and a natural fit; of course Company X should buy=
 Company Y. The timing hasn=E2=80=99t been right yet, but eventually the CE=
O gets around to it, meets with her counterpart at Company Y, hits it off, =
and quickly reaches a deal. Someone has to get a fee, and out of the 30 ban=
ks that showed the CEO=C2=A0pitchbooks saying =E2=80=9Cyou should buy Compa=
ny Y=E2=80=9D with supporting financial and structuring analysis,=C2=A0she =
picks the three best to work on the deal. The other 27 can think =E2=80=9Cy=
ou stole my intellectual property,=E2=80=9D but they are deluded.</li> </ul=
> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The reality might be <a href=3D"https://link=
